comments.body:
@ashley-cui Yes, I think we're thinking along the same lines. I've implemented point 1 and pushed for your review and will work on 2 and 3 in the coming days.

It looks like there are already some [system tests related to remote connections](https://github.com/containers/podman/blob/main/test/system/272-system-connection.bats) which spin up their own podman service, but only when already running as remote to begin with, which doesn't a whole lot of sense. I think the most straightforward thing to do would be to use those as a basis for the per-remote connection tests and spot checks.

I wonder if it might be worthwhile to treat the remote system tests from points 2 and 3, along with the existing tests mentioned above, differently to those for point 1 so there doesn't need to be a global podman service running for them, while still running them all in the single remotesystem target.

@meln5674 The reason behind removing the environment variables is that we cannot support env vars for every option that exists. Persistent configurations should be set in containers.conf, and one-off configurations should be set using a flag. Therefore, both the use cases for env vars are covered, so there's no reason to support an env var as well. 

What issues are you running into when removing the env var? Please feel free to push to another branch and link it, maybe I can help out there. 

As an aside, we're approaching a deadline soon of when we want this feature in. I'd strongly prefer only working on the system tests, and the integration and makefile target can be worked on in a followup PR, as it looks like there are still design discussions around that as well.
